This course focuses on implications of the mega projects committed by China instead of their technical aspects. The course content is meant to be comprehensive, integrated and relevant in some way to students' own discip1ir.e of study. After taking this course, students are expected to have a comprehensive understanding about the latest developments in China. Specifically, the expected learning outcomes shall include:

1. Understanding the environmental crisis of China and possible sustainable solutions;

2. Learning how to think critically in general, and understanding complex socioeconomic and environmental issues in particular;

3. Understanding the responses to new challenges in the 21st century with respect to sustainable development goals using China as an example; and

4. Update of useful knowledge about China to broaden/enhance students' job opportunities and employability.

By the end of the course, students are expected to be able to:

* Understand the concepts and explain the formation of different natural landscapes, landforms and phenomena across the planet;
* Understand the inter-relationships between different physical and human-induced processes in shaping natural landscapes and landforms in the terrestrial and marine environments;
* Assess the impacts of climate change on natural wonders, and evaluate different options of climate change mitigation and adaptation
* Identify the challenges faced by the world’s natural wonders, and develop sustainable solutions in their preservation and management; and
* Improve academic skills in critical thinking, researching, teamwork, presentation, essay editing and writing.

After taking this course, students will be able to:

1. describe and compare the major principles and practices of modern agriculture and those of permaculture;

2. analyse the ethical issues related to modern agriculture in contemporary societies;

3. formulate personal views on how to live more ethically with nature.

This course is built around the fundamental understanding of the technological, economic and social issues of robots, the basic components and subsystems that make up robots and the development of critical perspectives of new automation technologies. The cornerstone of the class involves evaluation of robotic roles in our daily lives and exploring potential solutions with robotic technology. Upon completion of the course, students should have achived the following outcomes:

a.understand the various components of robotic systems and how they work together;

b.appreciate the potential value of robotic technology to the society;

c.develop skills of concept exploration, critical thinking and teamwork.

After completing the course, students should be able to
• recall and understand the basic idea and steps of how life comes into being in the astronomical perspective;
• demonstrate their understanding of the relationship between various component topics of astrobiology;
• form their opinion of the implication of the scientific knowledge of the origin of life on human’s position in the universe and the history of the universe;
• gain intellectual perspectives and appreciation on the development of the astrobiology field in particular, and the multidisciplinary study of problem in general;
• understand the basic principles of scientific method through examples.

Students will be expected to

- comprehend, analyze, and apply some general knowledge of astronomy, especially on topics that are interesting, related to students’ daily life, and serving to reveal how physical laws are at work in the universe;

- comprehend the universality and powerfulness of the laws of physics, and their applications on a wide range of astronomical phenomena;

- apply thinking skills based on knowledge acquired in the study, and be able to solve basic problems in astronomy;

- comprehend and appreciate the beauty of the universe, and also the role played by astronomy in daily life;

- comprehend how a scientist approaches a problem, and applies the scientific methods to seek answers;

- express a critical mind by learning to confront beliefs with observations and evidence.

